T1  - The empirical determination of technology and expectations: A simplified procedure
AU  - Epstein, Larry G.
AU  - Yatchew, Adonis J.
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 27
IS  - 2
SP  - 235
EP  - 258
PY  - 1985
DA  - 1985/02/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(85)90090-9
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304407685900909
AB  - This paper makes three principal contributions to the growing body of empirically oriented research on dynamic factor demand systems that are based on the adjustment cost model of the firm. First, a simplified procedure is described for deriving demand and supply functions which are amenable to empirical estimation and which are consistent with intertemporal expected profit maximization and a general expectations formation process for future prices. Second, it is pointed out that estimation of a complete system of demand and supply functions permits the empirical identification of both the firm's technology and its expectations formation process. Finally, the procedure is applied to aggregate annual U.S. manufacturing data for the 1947-1977 period and the consistency of the data with the theoretical framework is investigated.
